# Personal marker list — template.
#
#   cp .personal-markers.example .personal-markers
#
# .personal-markers is gitignored and never leaves your machine. The pre-commit
# hook in .githooks/ refuses any commit where a marker appears in a staged file's
# contents or in its path.
#
# Format: one marker per line. Blank lines and #-comments are ignored.
# Matching is literal text, case-insensitive, anywhere in the line (substring).
#
# The hook also scans your commit identity — `git config user.email` and
# `user.name` — against this list, because the author line is published to
# permanent history just as file content is. See [identity-allow] at the bottom
# for the escape hatch when your public attribution name is itself a marker.
#
# Two rules of thumb:
#   - Prefer the shortest form that still catches every variant. YOUR_PROJECT
#     catches your-project-api, YOUR_PROJECTApp, and your_project.dev at once.
#   - Do not add anything that legitimately appears in this repository — the
#     public name of the project, its GitHub org, its license holder. A marker
#     that matches the README blocks every commit you will ever make. Use a full
#     email rather than a bare handle when the handle is also the public org.

# --- Identity -----------------------------------------------------------
YOUR_NAME
YOUR_FULL_NAME
you@example.com
you@YOUR_DOMAIN
YOUR_DOMAIN.com

# --- Machine ------------------------------------------------------------
# Home-directory paths leak the account name through pasted terminal output.
/Users/YOUR_USERNAME
/home/YOUR_USERNAME

# --- Private projects ---------------------------------------------------
YOUR_PROJECT
YOUR_OTHER_PROJECT
YOUR_PRIVATE_REPO

# --- Clients and engagements --------------------------------------------
CLIENT_NAME_ONE
CLIENT_NAME_TWO
CLIENT_PRODUCT_CODENAME

# --- Private infrastructure ---------------------------------------------
INTERNAL_HOSTNAME.example
YOUR_GITLAB_HOST

# --- Identity allowlist -------------------------------------------------
# Everything below [identity-allow] is permitted as the commit author name or
# email even though it matches a marker above. Matching here is exact and
# whole-value (still case-insensitive), not substring: "YOUR_NAME" allows the
# name "YOUR_NAME" and nothing else.
#
# This is scoped to commit identity alone. An allowlisted string remains blocked
# in file content and in paths — publishing a name on the author line is not the
# same as wanting it scattered through the source.
#
# Use it when your public attribution name is also a marker. If you commit under
# a noreply address and a handle that appear nowhere in your marker list, you do
# not need this section at all.
#
# [markers] switches back to ordinary markers if you prefer to keep going.
[identity-allow]
YOUR_NAME
YOUR_ID+YOUR_HANDLE@users.noreply.github.com
